#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:2
msgid "Authentication"
msgstr "认证"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:4
msgid ""
"Authentication is an **essential** part of most existing applications. "
"There are a lot of different approaches, strategies, and ways to handle "
"user authorization. What we eventually decide to use depends on the "
"particular application requirements and is strongly associated with their"
" needs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:10
msgid ""
"`Passport <https://github.com/jaredhanson/passport>`__ is the most "
"popular node.js authentication library, well-known by community and "
"successively used in many production applications. It’s really simple to "
"integrate this tool with **Nest** framework using dedicated passport "
"utilities. For demonstration purposes, we’ll set up both `passport-http-"
"bearer <https://github.com/jaredhanson/passport-http-bearer>`__ and "
"`passport-jwt <https://github.com/themikenicholson/passport-jwt>`__ "
"strategy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:20
msgid "Installation"
msgstr "Installation"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:22
msgid ""
"In order to start the adventure with this library, we have to install a "
"few fundamental packages. Additionally, we’ll start by implementing the "
"bearer strategy, and thus we need to install ``passport-http-bearer`` "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:32
msgid "Bearer strategy"
msgstr "Bearer strategy"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:34
msgid ""
"As has been said already, firstly, we’ll implement `passport-http-bearer "
"<https://github.com/jaredhanson/passport-http-bearer>`__ library. Bearer "
"tokens are typically used to protect API endpoints, and are often issued "
"using OAuth 2.0. The HTTP Bearer authentication strategy authenticates "
"users using a bearer token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:40
msgid ""
"Let’s start by creating the ``AuthService`` class that will expose a "
"single method, ``validateUser()`` which responsibility is to query user "
"using provided bearer **token**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:78
msgid ""
"The ``validateUser()`` method takes ``token`` as an argument. This token "
"is extracted from ``Authorization`` header that has been passed along "
"with HTTP request. The ``findOneByToken()`` method’s responsibility is to"
" validate if passed token truly exists and is associated with any "
"registered account in the database."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:84
msgid ""
"Once ``AuthService`` class is done, we have to create a corresponding "
"**strategy** that passport will use to authenticate requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:132
msgid ""
"The ``HttpStrategy`` uses ``AuthService`` to validate the token. When the"
" token is valid, passport allows further request processing. Otherwise, "
"the user receives ``401 Unauthorized`` response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:136
msgid "Afterwards, we can create the ``AuthModule``."
msgstr "Afterwards, we can create the ``AuthModule``."

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:154
msgid ""
"warning **Notice** In order to make use of ``UsersService``, the "
"``AuthModule`` imports ``UsersModule``. The internal implementation is "
"unimportant here and heavily depends on your technical project "
"requirements (e.g. database)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:159
#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:472
msgid ""
"Then, you can simply use the ``AuthGuard`` wherever you want to enable "
"the authentication."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:170
msgid ""
"The ``@AuthGuard()`` is imported from ``@nestjs/passport`` package. Also,"
" ``bearer`` is a name of the strategy that passport will make use of. Let"
" us check if endpoint is effectively secured. To ensure that everything "
"work correctly, we’ll perform a GET request to the ``users`` resource "
"without setting a valid token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:180
#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:491
msgid ""
"Application should respond with ``401 Unauthorized`` status code and "
"following response body:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:188
#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:499
msgid ""
"If you create a valid token beforehand and pass it along with the HTTP "
"request, the application will respectively identify a user, attach its "
"object to the request, and allow further request processing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:197
msgid "Default strategy"
msgstr "Default strategy"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:199
msgid ""
"To determine default passport behavior, you can register the "
"``PassportModule``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:221
msgid ""
"Once you set ``defaultStrategy``, you no longer need to manually pass the"
" strategy name in the ``@AuthGuard()`` decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:234
msgid ""
"warning **Notice** Keep in mind that either ``PassportModule`` or "
"``AuthModule`` has to be imported by every module that makes use of the "
"``AuthGuard``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:239
msgid "User object"
msgstr "User object"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:241
msgid ""
"When request is validated correctly, the user entity will be attached to "
"the request object and accessible through ``user`` property (e.g. "
"``req.user``). To change the property name, set ``property`` of the "
"options object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:251
msgid "Customize passport"
msgstr "Customize passport"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:253
msgid ""
"Depending on the strategy that is being used, passport takes a bunch of "
"properties that shape the library behavior. Use ``register()`` method to "
"pass down options object directly to the passport instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:262
msgid "Inheritance"
msgstr "Inheritance"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:264
msgid ""
"In most cases, ``AuthGuard`` will be sufficient. However, in order to "
"adjust either default error handling or authentication logic, you can "
"extend the class and override methods within a subclass."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:295
msgid ""
"info **Hint** In order to use your custom ``JwtAuthGuard``, you must add "
"it as a guard to your specific routes (e.g., "
"``@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard)``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:300
msgid "JWT strategy"
msgstr "JWT strategy"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:302
msgid ""
"A second described approach is to authenticate endpoints using a **JSON "
"web token** (JWT). To implement a JWT-based authentication flow, we need "
"to install required packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:310
msgid ""
"Once the installation process is done, we can focus on ``AuthService`` "
"class. We need to switch from the token validation to a payload-based "
"validation logic as well as provide a way to create a JWT token for the "
"particular user which then could be used to authenticate the incoming "
"request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:370
msgid ""
"info **Hint** The ``JwtPayload`` is an interface with a single property, "
"an ``email``, and represents decoded JWT token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:373
msgid ""
"In order to simplify an example, we created a fake user. The second step "
"is to create a corresponding ``JwtStrategy``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:428
msgid ""
"The ``JwtStrategy`` uses ``AuthService`` to validate the decoded payload."
" When the payload is valid (user exists), passport allows further request"
" processing. Otherwise, the user receives ``401 (Unauthorized)`` "
"response."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:433
msgid "Afterward, we can move to the ``AuthModule``."
msgstr "Afterward, we can move to the ``AuthModule``."

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:463
msgid ""
"info **Hint** In order to make use of ``UsersService``, the "
"``AuthModule`` imports ``UsersModule``. The internal implementation is "
"unimportant here. Besides, ``JwtModule`` has been registered statically. "
"To switch to asynchronous configuration, read more `here "
"<https://github.com/nestjs/passport>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:469
msgid ""
"Both expiration time and ``secretKey`` are hardcoded (in a real-world "
"application you should rather consider using environment variables)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:483
msgid ""
"Let us check if endpoint is effectively secured. To ensure that "
"everything work correctly, we’ll perform a GET request to the ``users`` "
"resource without setting a valid token."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:508
msgid "Example"
msgstr "Example"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:510
msgid ""
"A full working example is available `here "
"<https://github.com/nestjs/nest/tree/master/sample/19-auth>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:514
msgid "Multiple strategies"
msgstr "Multiple strategies"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:516
msgid ""
"Usually, you’ll end up with single strategy reused across the whole "
"application. However, there might be cases when you’d prefer to use "
"different strategies for different scopes. In the case of multiple "
"strategies, pass the second argument to the ``PassportStrategy`` "
"function. Generally, this argument is a name of the strategy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:526
msgid ""
"In above example, the ``jwt`` becomes the name of the ``JwtStrategy``. "
"Afterward, you can use ``@AuthGuard('jwt')``, just the same as before."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:530
msgid "GraphQL"
msgstr "GraphQL"

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:532
msgid ""
"In order to use ``AuthGuard`` together with `GraphQL </graphql/quick-"
"start>`__, you have to extend the built-in ``AuthGuard`` class and "
"override ``getRequest()`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:546
msgid ""
"We assumed that ``req`` (request) has been passed as a part of the "
"context value. We have to set this behavior in the module settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/authentication.rst:555
msgid "And now, context value will have ``req`` property."
msgstr "And now, context value will have ``req`` property."

